# Project workflow rules

## What counts as implementation
The ontology files (`ontology/*.ttl`, `ontology/*.owl`) ARE this repo's implementation, along
with the Python tools. Edits to any of them count as implementation changes.

## PRD drift detection
- The PRD at `docs/PRD.md` is the source of truth. Requirements carry stable `REQ-NNN` IDs.
- Never claim a requirement is implemented without a `file:line` reference.
- A test is not an implementation.
- After modifying implementation files, run `/prd-sync` before ending the session.

## Before solving any non-trivial problem (mandatory — do not ask first)
Run `/pattern-search <problem description>`. It calls the server-side `pattern-search` MCP tool
(hybrid vector + BM25 retrieval over `shared_patterns`) — do not hand-write CONTAINS/AQL queries
for this.

## After fixing a drift gap or discovering a reusable technique
Run `/pattern-save` to write the verified solution to shared memory.

## Ontology editing invariants
- Edit `ontology/aws.ttl`, then regenerate the OWL serialization:
  `venv/bin/python tools/sync_formats.py ttl-to-owl && venv/bin/python tools/sync_formats.py check`
- Run the test suite before committing (`tests/test_format_sync.py`, `tests/test_ontology_quality.py`,
  `tests/test_examples_validation.py`).
- Keep `owl:versionInfo` in sync with the latest CHANGELOG release.
- Stay within OWL 2 DL (no inverse-functional datatype properties; use `owl:hasKey` for keys).

## Session end checklist
- `/prd-sync` if implementation files changed
- `/pattern-save` for any technique worth sharing
- Check `.prd-drift-queue/` for queued change alerts
